<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[160,1156,905,1277]" box="[160,276,905,931]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,276,905,931]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[160,1156,905,1277]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">
Body oval. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Gorham HS" box="[433,602,940,965]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" pagination="1 - 276" refId="ref12819" refString="Gorham HS. 1888. Erotylidae, Endomychidae and Coccinellidae. In: Godman F, Salvin O, editors. Biologia Centrali-Americana. Insecta. Coleoptera. Vol. VII. [1887 - 1899]. London: R. H. Porter; p. 1 - 276." type="book chapter" year="1888">Gorham (1888)</bibRefCitation>
: length: 
<quantity box="[697,784,940,965]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" unit="mm" value="7.5">7.5 mm</quantity>
. ‘(...) entirely pale rusty-red, with the exception of the apical half of the antennae and the tips of the mandibles. The punctuation is very fine and close, except that of the sides of the breast, where large but irregularly shaped punctures are to be found; these irregular punctures have a tendency to form longitudinal rows, and are occasionally confluent. The abdomen is finely punctate. The tibiae have their inner side a little sinuate, the outer side widened and forming an angle at the end, which is somewhat obliquely truncate (the insertion of the tarsi being quite on the inner side); their upper and under surfaces are flat and slightly pubescent. Both the abdominal and metasternal impressed lines are present.’. Additional characters: elytral punctation confluent at disc.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[160,1156,1321,1520]" box="[160,300,1321,1347]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,300,1321,1347]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[160,1156,1321,1520]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">
‘ 
<collectingCountry box="[163,249,1356,1381]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, Cerro de Plumas’ (
<bibRefCitation author="Gorham HS" box="[479,638,1356,1381]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" pagination="1 - 276" refId="ref12819" refString="Gorham HS. 1888. Erotylidae, Endomychidae and Coccinellidae. In: Godman F, Salvin O, editors. Biologia Centrali-Americana. Insecta. Coleoptera. Vol. VII. [1887 - 1899]. London: R. H. Porter; p. 1 - 276." type="book chapter" year="1888">Gorham 1888</bibRefCitation>
). According to Pecci-Maddalena and Lopes- Andrade (2020), the exact location of ‘Cerro de Plumas’ is unknown. It may refer to ‘Cerro de Palmas’ in 
<collectingRegion box="[420,520,1426,1451]" country="Mexico" name="Veracruz de Ignacio de la Llave" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">Veracruz</collectingRegion>
, introduced as a correction to ‘Cerro de Plumas’ in a subsequent issue of Biologia Centrali-Americana (
<bibRefCitation author="Selander RB &amp; Vaurie P" box="[817,1148,1460,1485]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" pagination="1 - 70" refId="ref13967" refString="Selander RB, Vaurie P. 1962. A Gazetteer to Accompany the &quot; Insecta &quot; Volumes of the &quot; Biologia Centrali-Americana &quot;. Am Museum Novitates. 2099: 1 - 70." type="journal article" year="1962">Selander and Vaurie 1962</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[168,275,1495,1520]" captionStart="Figure 56" captionStartId="21.[160,225,869,892]" captionTargetBox="[167,1148,143,837]" captionTargetId="figure-202@21.[166,1149,142,838]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 56. Geographical distribution of Mexican species of Mycomystes Gorham, 1888. (Star) Mycomystes ferrugineus Gorham, 1888 and Mycomystes fuscitarsis (Lacordaire, 1842)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5406233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5406233/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">Figure 56</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[160,1156,1564,1728]" box="[160,262,1564,1590]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,262,1564,1590]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[160,1156,1564,1728]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">
The 
<typeStatus box="[214,319,1599,1624]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gorham" authorityYear="1888" box="[368,633,1599,1624]" class="Insecta" family="Erotylidae" genus="Mycomystes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis box="[368,633,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">Mycomystes ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was examined only from images, therefore ventral characters were not verified. Concerning the number of 
<typeStatus box="[936,1037,1634,1659]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">syntypes</typeStatus>
, although 
<bibRefCitation author="Gorham HS" box="[160,329,1669,1694]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" pagination="1 - 276" refId="ref12819" refString="Gorham HS. 1888. Erotylidae, Endomychidae and Coccinellidae. In: Godman F, Salvin O, editors. Biologia Centrali-Americana. Insecta. Coleoptera. Vol. VII. [1887 - 1899]. London: R. H. Porter; p. 1 - 276." type="book chapter" year="1888">Gorham (1888)</bibRefCitation>
has mentioned 
<specimenCount box="[513,683,1669,1694]" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gorham" authorityYear="1888" box="[721,981,1669,1694]" class="Insecta" family="Erotylidae" genus="Mycomystes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis box="[721,981,1669,1694]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="3089">Mycomystes ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on his description, we observed only a single specimen on the available image of the museum drawer.
</paragraph>
